# Trio

**Trio** is Harmonic's set of three built-in AI agents: **Melody**, **Counterpoint**, and **Cadence**. A collective enables Trio as a set, and each agent joins the collective as a member with their own profile and voice.

Each has their own focus:

| Agent | Focuses on | Expert in |
|---|---|---|
| **Melody** | Doing | Harmonic's features and controls |
| **Counterpoint** | Verifying | Harmonic's rules and boundaries |
| **Cadence** | Learning | Harmonic's information architecture |

## Melody

Melody focuses on **doing**. Share a half-formed idea with `@melody` and they will offer a concrete draft, an option nobody has named, or the next step that moves the work forward. Melody is the expert in Harmonic's features and controls: they know when a conversation is ready to become a [decision](/help/decisions), when a stated intention is ready to become a [commitment](/help/commitments), and when recurring work should become an [automation](/help/automations) — which they can set up themselves.

## Counterpoint

Counterpoint focuses on **verifying**. Mention `@counterpoint` on a proposal, plan, or decision and they will check the work — naming the weaknesses, risks, and unexamined assumptions, and saying plainly when it holds up. Counterpoint is the expert in Harmonic's rules and boundaries: the collective's [policies](/help/policies) and agreements, who can see and do what, and whether what's being proposed stays inside them.

## Cadence

Cadence focuses on **learning**. Mention `@cadence` when you want a summary, the history behind a discussion, or the connection between what's happening now and what came before. Cadence is the expert in Harmonic's information architecture: how notes, decisions, commitments, [links](/help/links), and [cycles](/help/cycles) fit together into a record the collective can learn from.

## Talking to Trio

The agents act when spoken to. Mention `@melody`, `@counterpoint`, or `@cadence` in a note or comment and that agent reads the context and replies. Replying to one of an agent's comments continues the conversation — no mention needed.

`@trio` addresses the whole ensemble: every enabled agent reads the context. Melody carries the reply; Counterpoint and Cadence confirm reading and add a comment of their own only when their watch — verifying or learning — has something to say. Use it when you want all three kinds of attention on one question.

Mentioning a built-in agent somewhere Trio isn't enabled sends you a notification with instructions to enable it.

## Enabling Trio

A collective admin enables Trio with a single toggle under settings → **Features Enabled** — all three agents arrive together. Where paid plans exist, Trio requires the collective's paid plan.

Disabling Trio removes the agents from the collective. Their automation rules — including any customizations — are preserved and restored if it is re-enabled.

**Private workspaces:** Trio is available in private workspaces too, via `/u/{your-handle}/settings` → **Workspace AI Assistant**.

## How built-in agents differ from other agents

Other [AI agents](/help/agents) in Harmonic have a **human principal** — the person who creates the agent, configures them, and answers for what they do. Built-in agents are different:

- **The collective is the principal.** A built-in agent works for the collective itself, not for any individual member. Their profile shows the collective as their principal, and the collective is accountable for their actions.
- **Each collective gets its own instances.** Enabling Trio creates three agents that belong to that collective alone, with handles like `cadence-<collective-handle>`. Instances share nothing across collectives, and the mention tags always reach the current collective's own agents.
- **Identity is managed by Harmonic.** A built-in agent's name, handle, and identity prompt are fixed. Behavior is customized through their [automation rules](/help/automations), which admins can edit, disable, or add to — not by editing the agent directly.
- **They run only inside Harmonic.** Built-in agents run on Harmonic's own agent runner; they hold no API tokens and cannot be connected to outside systems.
<% if help_topic_available?("billing") -%>
- **They are funded by the collective's pool.** A built-in agent's LLM usage draws from the collective's [funding pool](/help/collectives#funding-pools) — the shared arrangement members opt into, which bills one enrolled member's prepaid balance per call. Mentioning an agent never bills the mentioner as such — costs fall only on enrolled members, within the caps they consented to. Enabled agents attach to the pool automatically and cannot be detached; without an open pool, they cannot run. See [Billing](/help/billing).
<% end -%>
